<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101137380951547></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101137380951547><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=101137380951547>RE: I have returned</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=101137380951547#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=126085><span id=Scholar>The Honorable MentalSword</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>49 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 18th 12:10 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.43]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There are some serious sound issues in EQ.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you go to the Developer's Corner on the official EQ site, you can see hundreds of sound related posts.<br><br>I had an SBLive! XGamer, and upgraded to a SB Audigy Gamer with no improvement.<br><br>The best results I've seen have been from those using a Turtle Beach card.  Although there are also my SB users who are fine (they mostly seem to be AMD user's though, myself and other's with Intel based systems seem to be the majority with problems).<br><br>As jcasetnl observed, the sound routines in game are being denied processor time in some configurations.  This is the cause of stuck or &quot;sustaining&quot; notes.  Anyone who remembers the birth of 3D PC gaming and tried at one time to get Wolf3D running on a 286 16Mhz w/2MB RAM, remembers how important available clock cycles are to sound.  Any time the processor stays at 100% utilization while music is trying to play, when the sound card reaches the end of its buffer it will either hold or repeat the last note played until the processor has time to load it with more music.<br><br>Given the poor frame rates, lag, missed clicks and keystrokes, and choppy sound that seem to make up most people's problems, it sounds to me like the game is wasting a lot of clock cycles somewhere...  My personal speculation is that the development team is still not using DirectPlay for the connectivity portion of the game.  I'm guessing that they use the DirectX routines for video, sound, and input, but their own in-house routines for the networking.  And somewhere therein lies a conflict.  Just my guess though based on all the problems I've read about and/or experienced.<br><br>Anyway, I agree with jcasetnl, just turn the sound down low and try to ignore it.  I have had no sound effects what-so-ever and very poor music since December.  After a while you'll just forget that the game should even have sound.  =(<br><br>&nbsp;<br>-Maintaining the Honor of Test</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
